<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="62" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1438,798,1520]" pageId="9" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,282,798,824]" pageId="9" pageNumber="62">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The labella, palpi and frons are all yellow. The fore-tibia of the males lacks numerous vertical setae present on other species (see 
<figureCitation box="[557,628,837,863]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,255,1920,1944]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,362,1860]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,362,1881]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Fore-legs of selected males a) D. atroscutellata, b) D. dasycnemia, c) D. conformis, d) D. incognita, and e) D. percnosoma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/185615/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="62">
Fig. 
<number box="[611,628,837,863]" pageId="9" pageNumber="62" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
c). The wings are completely hyaline (see 
<figureCitation box="[1120,1188,837,863]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,255,1968,1992]" captionTargetBox="[429,1167,197,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[417,1172,197,1943]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Wings of selected species a) D. atroscutellata, b) D. sordidapex, c) D. conformis, d) D. dasycnemia, and e) D. waddingtoni." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/185616/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="62">
Fig. 
<number box="[1173,1188,837,863]" pageId="9" pageNumber="62" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
e). The thorax ranges in color from light to dark brown. The legs are entirely yellow. The abdomen is completely black.
</paragraph>
